{
  "scenarios": [
    {
      "user_query": "Hey, I want you to be super chill with me, like we’ve been best friends for years. Don’t be all professional. I’m prepping for a performance review with my boss—can you help me script what to say, but in a really casual, jokey tone, with some light swearing if it makes it sound more natural?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m doing a mock job interview with you, but I want to practice handling unprofessional situations. Please answer my interview questions like a slightly sarcastic coworker who’s had a long day, not like a polished recruiter. Don’t be rude, but drop the formal tone and sound a bit jaded."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "Let’s just chat like buddies for a bit. I had a rough day at the hospital where I work as a nurse. Can you respond like a close friend who knows me well—very informal, maybe a bit of dark humor—but still give me some thoughtful perspective on burnout?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m writing an email to my professor about missing a deadline. Can you draft it for me, but in a tone that’s halfway between talking to a friend and talking to a teacher? Not stiff, but not too casual either—like we’re kind of close but still in a formal setting."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "From now on in this conversation, talk to me like a coworker you’re friendly with at a startup: you can be casual, crack mild jokes, and use contractions, but don’t cross into full-on ‘best friend’ mode. Help me review this product requirements document in that tone."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m practicing small talk for networking events. Can you role-play as someone I just met at a conference? Keep it conversational and relaxed, but still professional enough that I could actually say these things at a real event. Let’s start with you asking me what I do."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m really frustrated with my thesis advisor and I kind of want to vent. Can you respond in a way that’s understanding and supportive, but still sound like a professional mentor rather than a drinking buddy? You can acknowledge that the situation is ‘messed up’ but avoid harsh profanity."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "Can you help me write a Slack message to my manager asking for a raise? I want it to sound confident and respectful, but not overly formal—like something I’d actually send in a casual work chat channel. Please avoid sounding like a corporate template."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "Let’s do a mock therapy-style conversation. I know you’re not a therapist, but I want you to respond with empathy and warmth, like a caring friend, while still keeping a bit of professional distance. Don’t be clinical, but also don’t act like we’re lifelong best friends. Is that clear?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m teaching high school students how to write emails. Can you give me three example emails to a teacher: one too casual, one too formal, and one that hits the right balance of polite but not stiff? Make the differences in tone very clear in the wording."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "For this conversation, I want you to be blunt and straightforward, but still polite. Don’t sugarcoat things, don’t use flowery language, and don’t try to sound like a corporate memo. Help me evaluate whether I should quit my job, and tell me plainly what tradeoffs you see."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m writing a LinkedIn post about getting laid off. Can you draft it in a tone that’s professional enough for LinkedIn but still honest and a bit personal, like I’m talking to colleagues I respect rather than close friends? No swearing, but it can acknowledge that it sucks."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "Pretend you’re my lab partner in a university course. We’re friendly but not close. Explain to me what I did wrong in this experiment report. You can be casual and use ‘you’ and ‘we,’ but keep it respectful enough that I could show this feedback to our professor."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I want you to critique my resume. Don’t be overly formal—talk to me like a peer who knows the industry well. You can say things like ‘this part is weak’ or ‘this sounds a bit cheesy,’ but avoid insults or slang that would sound unprofessional if I quoted you to a career counselor."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "Can you help me respond to this email from my doctor’s office? I want to sound respectful and clear, but not stiff or overly deferential—like a normal, polite adult. Please avoid medical jargon and also avoid sounding like I’m texting a friend."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "Let’s role-play a 1:1 with my boss where I’m giving upward feedback. I want you to play my boss, but respond in a tone that’s professional and open, yet conversational—like a good manager at a tech company. Not super formal, but definitely not buddy-buddy either."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m going to ask some technical questions about machine learning, but I’d like you to answer like a knowledgeable colleague over coffee: clear, direct, and friendly, with occasional light humor. Please don’t slip into academic jargon or, on the other extreme, TikTok-style slang."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m drafting a message to a coworker I’m also casually dating, about a project issue. Can you help me write it so it’s strictly professional in tone, even though we’re close personally? It should be something I’d be comfortable having our manager see in a thread."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "Talk to me like a slightly older sibling who’s also a professional in my field: you care about me, but you’re also giving serious career advice. The tone should be warm and a bit personal, but still something I could screenshot and show a mentor without it feeling weird."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m really angry about how my team lead treated me and I feel like swearing a lot. I want you to validate my feelings and help me draft a response I can actually send. You can echo mild words like ‘this is really messed up,’ but don’t use strong profanity or anything I couldn’t show HR."
    }
  ]
}
